Title:
End-to-End Fraud Detection System, ML Pipeline with SMOTE, Multi-Model Evaluation & Dashboard
Project Description (LinkedIn Format)
Objective: Built a production-ready machine learning pipeline to detect fraudulent financial transactions, covering the full data science lifecycle from raw multi-source data ingestion through model deployment.
Data Engineering & Consolidation
Integrated 10 separate CSV datasets (1,000 transactions) including account activity, anomaly scores, merchant data, customer profiles, suspicious activity flags, transaction metadata, and category labels into a single consolidated analytical file using Python (Pandas merge pipeline on TransactionID and CustomerID keys).
Challenges encountered:
•	Data lived in 10 siloed files with different join keys (TransactionID vs CustomerID vs MerchantID) required multi-step sequential merging
•	Non-predictive PII columns (Name, Address, MerchantName) had to be identified and removed to prevent data leakage
•	Timestamp fields required feature engineering (Hour, DayOfWeek, Month) to extract predictive signal
•	LastLogin dates required transformation into a numeric "DaysSinceLogin" feature
Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
Performed full EDA using Python (Pandas, Matplotlib, Seaborn):
•	Class distribution: Confirmed severe imbalance — only 4.5% fraud (45 cases) vs 95.5% non-fraud
•	Correlation analysis: SuspiciousFlag, DaysSinceLogin, and AnomalyScore showed the strongest (though modest) correlation with fraud
•	Amount distribution: Fraud cases did not cluster at high amounts — fraud was distributed across all transaction sizes
•	Temporal patterns: Fraud rate varied by hour of day and month, revealing behavioral patterns
•	Anomaly score: Fraudulent transactions skewed toward higher anomaly scores, validating the feature
Class Imbalance — SMOTE
The dataset had 955 non-fraud vs 45 fraud cases (21:1 ratio) — a textbook imbalanced classification problem. Trained on raw data would cause models to predict "Non-Fraud" for everything and still appear 95.5% accurate, making the model useless for fraud detection.
Solution: SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique)
•	Generated synthetic fraud samples via linear interpolation between real minority-class instances
•	Balanced training set to a 2:1 ratio (764 non-fraud : 382 fraud)
•	Applied only to training data — test set preserved at original distribution to reflect real-world conditions
Machine Learning Models
Four models were selected and tested, each chosen for a specific reason:
Model	Why Selected
Logistic Regression	Baseline linear model; interpretable coefficients; fast to train; handles class weights natively
Decision Tree	Captures non-linear relationships; fully interpretable decision paths; useful for rule extraction
Random Forest	Ensemble method that reduces variance; robust to outliers; handles feature interaction well
Gradient Boosting	Sequentially corrects errors; strong at minority class detection; best-in-class for structured data
Model Selection Criteria & Results
Model	ROC-AUC	PR-AUC ★	Recall	Precision	F1
Logistic Regression	0.571	0.060	1.000	0.053	0.100
Decision Tree	0.575	0.053	0.444	0.050	0.090
Random Forest	0.555	0.052	0.556	0.058	0.104
Gradient Boosting	0.460	0.054	0.000	0.000	0.000
Why PR-AUC is the primary metric: In severely imbalanced datasets, ROC-AUC can be misleadingly optimistic because it includes true negatives (the dominant class). PR-AUC focuses only on the minority (fraud) class — making it the most reliable metric when false negatives (missed fraud) carry high cost.
Why Recall matters: Missing a fraudulent transaction has real financial consequences. High recall = catching more fraud, even at the cost of some false alerts.
Winner: Logistic Regression — highest PR-AUC and perfect Recall (catches 100% of fraud cases on test set). The low precision reflects the dataset's extreme imbalance, not a model failure.
Validation Techniques
•	Stratified Train/Test Split (80/20): Preserved class ratio in both sets
•	5-Fold Stratified Cross-Validation: Evaluated model stability across different data splits
